From superficial to deep, the layers of the thoracic wall are:
the skin (composed of the epidermis     and dermis)
the hypodermis      or superficial fascia      (loose CT and adipose)
deep fascia (not shown; consists of a thin layer of dense irregular CT)
ribs, their associated skeletal muscles, major nerves, and blood & lymphatic vessels
parietal pleura, a serous membrane that covers, and is adhered to, the inner thoracic wall.

The thoracic body wall is innervated by branches of the thoracic spinal nerves, T1-T12. Branches of the dorsal and ventral rami of the thoracic spinal nerves, containing somatic motor fibres, sensory fibres and sympathetic postganglionic fibres, ramify to innervate their target tissues in all of these layers.
above or superficial to; the epidermis is superficial to the dermis.
below or deep to; the hypodermis is deep to the dermis of the skin.
a connective tissue layer as observed with the naked eye; i.e. at the gross level, rather than under a microscope
